AN ACT relating to debt; establishing coerced debt as an affirmative defense in
certain civil actions to collect an unsecured consumer debt; setting
forth requirements for asserting the affirmative defense of coerced
debt; requiring a court to take certain actions upon finding that a debt is
a coerced debt; authorizing certain claims and remedies; revising
provisions governing the presumption of intent to defraud in the
issuance of certain instruments; and providing other matters properly
relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law governs the collection of debt by certain persons in this State, including,
2 without limitation, collection agencies and private debt collectors. (See, e.g., chapters 353C
3 and 649 of NRS) Section 1 of this bill establishes that, in any civil action to collect an
4 unsecured consumer debt, a debtor may assert as an affirmative defense that the debt is a
5 coerced debt. Section 1 also: (1) sets forth the requirements for asserting the affirmative
6 defense of coerced debt; and (2) requires a court, upon finding that a debt is a coerced debt, to
7 order the creditor to cease collection efforts and, if applicable, correct certain records. In
8 addition, section 1 authorizes: (1) the creditor to join a third party who may be liable for the
9 coerced debt or amend its complaint to assert a claim against any such person; and (2) the
10 debtor to recover attorney’s fees and costs from the person who coerced the debt.
11 Existing law makes it a crime to issue a check or draft against insufficient or no
12 funds with intent to defraud. (NRS 205.130) Under existing law, intent to defraud and
13 knowledge of insufficient funds are presumed to exist if payment of the instrument is
14 refused by the drawee when presented in the usual course of business, unless the drawer
15 pays the full amount due within 5 days after receiving notice from the drawee or the
16 holder. (NRS 205.132) Section 1.5 of this bill provides that, for the purpose of
17 determining whether a check or draft is presented in the usual course of business, a
18 check or draft that constitutes a credit instrument is deemed to be presented in the usual
19 course of business if it is presented not more than 2 years after the date on which the
20 credit instrument is issued.

