THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 597 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
2 section to read as follows:
3 1. In any civil action to collect an unsecured consumer debt, it is an
4 affirmative defense under applicable court rules that the debt is a coerced debt.
5 2. To assert the affirmative defense of coerced debt, a debtor must submit to
6 the court:
7 (a) A written attestation that includes, without limitation:
8 (1) A statement that clearly identifies the specific debt the debtor asserts
9 is a coerced debt;
10 (2) A description of the circumstances under which the alleged coerced
11 debt was incurred, including specific facts supporting the allegation;
12 (3) Except as otherwise provided in subsection 4, any information known
13 to the debtor regarding the identity and contact information of the person alleged
14 to have coerced the debtor into incurring the debt; and
15 (4) A statement indicating the number of times the debtor has previously
16 asserted the affirmative defense of coerced debt in any action or proceeding
17 before a court in this State or any other state, including whether each such
18 assertion was successful or unsuccessful; and
19 (b) A copy of at least one of the following documents:
20 (1) A police report, investigative report or complaint which the debtor
21 filed with a law enforcement agency that is relevant to establishing that the debt
22 is a coerced debt;
23 (2) A report filed with the Federal Trade Commission indicating that the
24 debtor is a victim of identity theft; or
25 (3) A temporary or extended order for protection against domestic
26 violence issued by a court of competent jurisdiction or other court record that is
27 relevant to establishing that the debt is a coerced debt.
28 3. If the court determines that the debt identified by the debtor pursuant to
29 subparagraph (1) of paragraph (a) of subsection 2 constitutes a coerced debt:
30 (a) The court shall order the creditor to immediately cease all collection
31 efforts related to the coerced debt and, if applicable, to take reasonable steps to
32 correct any consumer credit report or similar record to reflect that the debt is a
33 coerced debt;
34 (b) The creditor may join any third party who is or may be liable for the
35 coerced debt or amend its complaint to assert a claim against any such person;
36 and
37 (c) The debtor is entitled to recover from the person who coerced the debtor
38 into incurring the coerced debt reasonable attorney’s fees and costs, but may not
39 recover such fees and costs from the creditor.
40 4. If the debtor believes that providing the information required by
41 subparagraph (3) of paragraph (a) of subsection 2 is likely to result in abuse to
42 the debtor or an immediate family member of the debtor, the debtor may, in lieu
43 of providing the information, submit to the court a statement, signed and sworn
44 to or affirmed by the debtor, that such disclosure is likely to result in abuse to the
45 debtor or an immediate family member of the debtor.
46 5. As used in this section:
47 (a) “Coerced debt” means an unsecured consumer debt or any part thereof
48 incurred for personal, family or household purposes as a result of fraud, duress,

